{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e545f768-c934-4e9f-a7d3-feaa4e44be03","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe report confirms it: the bottleneck is **MSBuild process cold-start and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps MSBuild loaded in-process. The project file itself is clean — nothing to fix there.\n\n## Recommendations (most to least impactful)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nKeeps the process alive, watches for file changes, and rebuilds incrementally — no cold start:\n```\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server\nReuses a long-lived MSBuild process across CLI invocations, eliminating startup overhead. Set this environment variable in your shell profile:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\nOr create a `Directory.Build.rsp` file in the repo root so the entire team benefits:\n```\n-nodeReuse:true\n```\n\n### 3. Ensure the Roslyn shared compiler is active\nThis is on by default but worth confirming — it keeps `VBCSCompiler` warm between builds:\n```xml\n<UseSharedCompilation>true</UseSharedCompilation>\n```\n\n### 4. For edit-build-**run** cycles, use `dotnet watch run`\nCombines build + execute with file watching — ideal for the tightest inner loop:\n```\ndotnet watch run\n```\n\n**The single biggest win** is switching from repeated `dotnet build` to `dotnet watch build`. It sidesteps the entire MSBuild startup cost that the report identifies, matching the Visual Studio experience.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3c7830c4-301d-4e70-9b81-83acea966be2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've verified analyzers aren't the issue and incremental build targets work correctly.\n\nThe key insight from the report is: \"The overhead seems to come from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\"\n\nThis is a well-known issue. Visual Studio keeps MSBuild loaded in-process (warm), so it avoids the startup cost. The CLI starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThe main recommendations are:\n\n1. **Use `dotnet build-server`** - .NET 8+ has an MSBuild server that keeps MSBuild warm between builds. This can be enabled via environment variable `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or the project property.\n\n\n2. **Use `dotnet watch build`** - instead of repeatedly invoking `dotnet build` manually, this keeps the process alive and watches for file changes, eliminating startup overhead entirely.\n3. **Enable graph-based builds** with the `/graph` flag for better parallelization.\n\nFor this specific scenario, the biggest wins are enabling the MSBuild server in .NET 8+ to keep the build process warm between invocations, or switching to `dotnet watch build` to avoid process startup altogether.\n\nThe real bottleneck here is the MSBuild process startup cost on each `dotnet build` call. In .NET 7 and later, the MSBuild server can be enabled via the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable to keep the build infrastructure resident in memory.","outputTokens":1125,"requestId":"0412:2211CA:440F1E:4FADCE:69F004B7"},"id":"e8a416ad-1a6d-4994-b525-8adb16990f71","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:52:33.223Z","parentId":"8c8f5db7-318a-4829-8182-42be6e5af569"}
